// Processed by 'GLSL Shader Shrinker'
// (https://github.com/deanthecoder/GLSLShaderShrinker)
//
// Hannibal Lecter's cell from the 'Silence of the Lambs' movie.
// I wish my GPU has enough power to render some posters and drawings
// on the cell wall! Probably quite doable if I used multiple buffers,
// but I always try to make my code single-buffer with no predefined
// textures.
//
// Tricks to ('try and'!) get the performance:
// - The stone walls are flat planes, and the material is bump-mapped.
//   Adding texture by adjusting the SDF would look nice, but increase
//   the number of steps in the march loop.
//   (I use dFdx and dFdy to approximate the normal of the texture.)
// - The material code (lights()) is called _outside_ the raymarch loop
//   to keep the loop code minimal (should the compiler decide to unroll it).
// - The glass is a flat plane, so the normal passed into 'reflect()'
//   can be hard-coded.
// - The FBM noise function is only called once in lights(), and then used
//   by several materials.
// - Lots of use of abs() to mirror along axis.
//   (There's only one 'actual' prison cell - The other is mirrored.)
// - Use of fract() on the x-axis to repeat the holes in the glass.
//
// Thanks to Evvvvil, Flopine, Nusan, BigWings, Iq, Shane,
// Blackle, totetmatt, byt3_m3chanic, and a bunch of others for sharing
// their time and knowledge! If you want to get into shader coding, I'd
// recommend giving them a 'Google'.

